          rec: "At this stage, the goal is reproducibility and automation, not scale. (1) Migrate from notebooks to scripts: your training code should be a Python script (train.py) with CLI arguments for hyperparameters, runnable from the command line. The notebook was for exploration; the script is for production. (2) Track experiments: use MLflow (open-source, self-hosted, tracks parameters + metrics + artifacts + model versions — the standard choice for teams that want control) or Weights & Biases (SaaS, better visualization, built-in hyperparameter sweep, collaborative — $50/user/month for Teams, free for individuals). Each training run records: git commit hash, data version (hash of training data), all hyperparameters, all evaluation metrics, and the trained model artifact. (3) Automate retraining: a cron job or Airflow DAG that runs weekly: fetch latest data → compute features → train → evaluate → if better than current production model, register in model registry → alert human for review. (4) Use managed training: AWS SageMaker Training ($0.30–30/hr depending on instance), Google Vertex AI Training, or even a single GPU cloud instance (vast.ai for cheapest spot GPUs, ~$0.50/hr for A100). Technology comparison: MLflow (open-source, comprehensive — experiment tracking + model registry + model serving — strength: no vendor lock-in, huge community; weakness: UI is functional but not beautiful, self-hosting requires some ops). Weights & Biases (SaaS, best visualization and collaboration — strength: gorgeous dashboards, built-in sweep, team features; weakness: SaaS cost, data leaves your network). DVC (Data Version Control — git for data — strength: version large datasets alongside code; weakness: learning curve, doesn't do experiment tracking well on its own).",
